Analyzing the Success of China as a Foreign Aid Donor
After decades of economic success and rapid growth from the 1970s onwards, China
has slowly emerged as a new potential global super power in terms of political and economic
strength and influence.
1
The provision of foreign aid from China to Africa has recently been
brought to light by news media outlets
2
due to the recent completion of many large scale
infrastructure projects across Sub-Saharan Africa funded by the Chinese Government.
3
What
is unique about the investments China has made in the Global South is that their
methodologies move away from what is conventional in terms of traditional donor countries’
foreign aid. The predominant underlying contrast between the two methodologies is that the
majority of foreign aid given by China has no political conditionality and focuses on trade and
direct investment. The methodologies of traditional donor countries are generally offered
with political conditions and tends to support other aspects of development with the
Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) as a framework.
4
The main justifying arguments for
political conditionality given by traditional aid donors is that the conditions are necessary to
promote democracy and liberalization within the Global South, and that they work as a means
for development. Yet decades later and with billions of dollars invested, there are many
countries which are still not democracies, not liberalized and still severely underdeveloped.

Introducing Chinese Foreign Aid: Principles, Concepts and Methods of Foreign
Aid in China
The main underlying concepts for Chinese aid are the movement away from tied aid
and focusing on the combination of economic cooperation and aid to promote national self-
reliance in countries in the Global South. These are further elaborated through different
principles and methods - the main ones being: The Eight Principles for Economic Aid and
Technical Assistance to Other Countries, the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence, the
Trinity Development Cooperation, and South-South cooperation.
13
The Eight Principles for Economic Aid and Technical Assistance to Other Countries
were developed for 1963 to 1964, and are as follows: mutual benefit; no conditions attached;
the no-interest or low-interest loans would not create a debt burden for the recipient country;
to help the recipient nation develop its economy, not to create its dependence on China; to
help the recipient country with project that needs less capital and quick returns; the aid in

Analyzing Successes of China’s Foreign Aid
To analyze the successes of China’s foreign aid, we can decompose the legitimacy of
the common criticisms posed in the previous section. One of the largest criticisms was that
China uses foreign aid as a diplomatic tool to progress state power rather than because it is
morally obliged to do so because it is capable. This criticism is not unique to Chinese foreign
aid, as many traditional donors have been accused of similarly abusing the vulnerability of
recipient countries in order to achieve state ends. For these states they do so mainly through
trade barriers and economic policy. For example, West African farmers produce cotton more
cheaply and in a more ecologically sustainable way than the 25,000 highly mechanized cotton
growers in the United States. However, the United States pays a total of US$3 billion dollars
each year in subsidies to cotton growers in the United States, enabling them to undercut the
West African cotton growers on the world market.
37
Many other countries partake in national
subsidies in order to undercut other countries and give themselves comparative advantage
also. The elimination of all agricultural subsidies and a 50 percent reduction in nonagricultural
tariffs, calculated by economists Kym Anderson and Alan Winters, would result in a global
economic gain of at least US$96 billion dollars annually of which US$30 billion would go to
the developing world.
38
China may be emulating other countries by manipulating more
vulnerable states for the sake of augmenting state power, but that cannot diminish the
criticism nonetheless. If every country is doing something to inhibit the development of the

traditionally posed for so long. The Global South now has more choices in this sense, and
could in the future have more countries following in breaking away from traditional methods

Appendix
Definitions
Definition 1:
ODA is defined by the Development Assistance Committee (DAC) of the OECD as: “those flows
to countries and territories on the DAC list of ODA Recipients and to multilateral institutions
which are: i) provided by official agencies, including state and local governments, or by their
executive agencies; and ii) each transaction of which: a) is administered with the promotion
of the economic development and welfare of developing countries as its main objective; and
b) is concessional in character and conveys a grant element of at least 25% (calculated at a
rate of discount of 10%).”
Citation: “Official Development Assistance – Definition and Coverage.” Official Development Assistance –
Definition and Coverage - OECD, Organization for Economic Co-Operation and Development,
www.oecd.org/dac/stats/officialdevelopmentassistancedefinitionandcoverage.htm.
